  "prompt": "What is the square root of 40 in radical form?",
  "response": "The square root of 40 can be simplified and expressed in radical form by following these steps:\n\n1. **Factorize the Number:**  \n   Break down 40 into its prime factors.  \n   \\( 40 = 4 \\times 10 = 2^2 \\times 2 \\times 5 \\)\n\n2. **Simplify the Square Root:**  \n   \\[\n   \\sqrt{40} = \\sqrt{4 \\times 10} = \\sqrt{4} \\times \\sqrt{10} = 2 \\times \\sqrt{10}\n   \\]\n\nSo, the square root of 40 in its simplest radical form is:\n\n\\[\n\\sqrt{40} = 2\\sqrt{10}\n\\]",
